{"/service/ndnp/ndhi/batch_ndhi_jemhadar_ver01/data/sn85042243/00383346162/1937112701/0782.xml":{"full_text":"CHARGE TRAII\nWITH CRIPPLING\nBUS OPERATIONS\nGreyhound Heads Ask $6,300,\n000 Damages Following\nStrike Violence\nCleveland. Nov. 27\u2014(JP\u2014Greyhound\nT.tn\u00ab filed nine suits in federal court\nSaturday asking $6,300,000 damages\nfrom the Brotherhood of Railroad\nTrainmen and 30 officers and mem\nbers.\nThe action followed arrests in vari\nout cities as violence continued in a\nstrike of bus drivers affiliated with\nthe B. R. T, The strike was called\nThursday to enforce demands for a\nclosed shop and wage increases.\nAt Syracuse, N. Y., two buses were\nstoned and police were hard pressed to\nhandle a crowd they estimated at 300\npjrsons that attempted to halt bus\nmovements.\nEleven men were held by Washing\nton police after a bus driver was\nforced to a curb and beaten. Two\nCleveland strikers were arraigned on\ndisorderly conduct charges.\n\"Damaging and destroying tires,\nwindows, brakes and various part* of\nmotor buses and other equipment,\"\n\"threatening and intimidating em\nployes\" and \"intimidating prospective\npassengers\" were cited as alleged of\nfenses.\nThe companies charged the strike\nwas called to \"restrict, limit and\ncripple the motor bus operations with\na view to restoring the patronage of\nthe motor bus operators to the rail'\nroads and increasing the number of\nrailroad trainmen employed by the\nrailroads.\"\nThe brotherhood has member* in\nboth transportation industries.\nASK SUPPORT OF\nRAILROAD LOCALS\nChicago. Nov. 27. WP) Striking\nGreyhound bus drivers sought the\n\"moral and financial support\" of 6,000\nrailroad trainmen in a meeting Sal'\nurday of 25 chairmen of locals of the\nBrotherhood of Railway Trainmen\nThe bus drivers are affiliated with\nthe brotherhood. Secretary Rex Tay\nlor of the busmen said the railroad\nlocals \"will pledge full support of the\nstrike.\"\nAdditional Markets\nGRAI\\ REVIEW\nMinneapolis, Nov. 2\".\u2014iff)\u2014(U. S. D.\nA.)\u2014Southern hemisphere crop news\navaln dominated world wheat markets\nduring the week ended Friday, No\nvember 26, and with harvesting pro\ngressing satisfactorily In Australia\nand more favorable weather condi\ntions in Argentina, world wheat mar\nkets generally showed an easy tone.\nBuenos Aires quotations were Inde\npendently weak because of the more\nfavorable Argentina situation and\ncabled reports from that country\nstated that the quality of some of the\n\u2022arly harvested grain was better than\n\u2022xpectations and showed good to ex\ncellent quality.\nForeign demand for North American\nwheat continued disappointingly light\nand this was a further depressing fac\ntor at Winnipeg and Lnited States\nmarkets. Continued weakness In se\ncurities markets also added to the\nunssttlement.\nReceipts of cash wheat were light\nand totaled only 07 cars at Minne\napolis and 22 at Duluth.\nMinneapolis December wheat de\nclined l-ttc for the week, closing Fri\nday at 97%c.\nDuluth December durum advanced\nHe\nnet for the week, closing Friday\nat S3 He.\nDecember rye fluctuated irregularly\nwith wheat and finished S-Hc net low\ner for the week, closing Friday at\n\u2022I He.\nOats fluctuated within a narrow\nrange Minneapolis December oats de\nclined \\c, closing Friday at 27c.\nBarley held fairly steady. Minne\napolis December barley advanced He\nfor the week, closing Friday at 48 Kc.\nFlax, after fluctuating over a wide\nrange, finished at the same figure\nwhich prevailed a week ago. Minne\napolis December flax closed Friday at\n?r\u00bbv*\nWALL STRKET REVIEW\nNew York, Nov. 27.\u2014MV-After\nlurching around this week the stock\nmarket rallied.\nAt ths close of the period there was\na brisk demand for utility and build\ning material shares. Buying energy\nspread rapidly to other groups, not\nably steels, coppers, oils, rails and\nmotors.\nBrokers said the Bwlngs provided a\npicture of Wall Street's unusually\nrapid shifts of opinion. This hot\nand-oold attitude, they said, resulted\nfrom the conflict presented by-news\nfrom Washington and signs of furth\ner business recession.\nVeterans interpreted the Washing\nton reports as follows: The adminis\ntration Is anxious to co-operate with\ngeneral business to the end of bring\ning a freer flow of capital Into pro\nductive channels. It would like to see\nthe utilities spend freely for construc\ntion. It would like to help bring a\nspurt in building. And It would like\nto Iron out tax problems. As some\nsaw It, progress was being made to\nward these ends, but It was still too\nearly to say how soon action could\nbe translated Into terms of wider em\nployment and business revival In\ntrade and Industry.\nThe steel Industry dropped Its\noperations again for the tenth conse\noutlve weekly loss. Motor production\nwas down. Freight carloadlngs\nshowed a more than seasonal reces\nsion. Demand for electric power was\nstill unaggressive. Retail trade got\na boost from colder weather in some\nparts of the country In others losses\nruled.\nThe bond market enjoyed a run-up\nafter Thanksgiving Day. U. 8. gov\nernment loans were steady and quiet.\nThe average of commodity prices\ndrifted to a new low for more than a\nyear.\nIn spite of the wide spread of its\nfront legs, the English bulldog passes\nits hind legs outside of the front legs\nwhen running.\nHomanls suffered the greatest\naverage loss In the World War, 44.76\npar cant of her men under arms.\nAcousticon Institute of\nBiamarck\nWearing Aids, Parts and\nBONHAM BROTHERS\nItliNrtkK\nlorly or Late\nMM beer Is ee\n\u2022er pr\nte every sea.\nCHURCHILL\nN. D. GRAIN DISPLAY\nExhibit at Chicago Expoaitlan\nIncludes Seed Crown by\nSlope Residents\nChicago, Nov.\n71.\u2014(JP)\u2014North\nWeather Report\nWEATHHR FORECAST\nFor Bismarck and vicinity: Gen\nerally fair tonight Sunday Increasing\ncloudiness and not so cold, with possi\nbly snow.\nFor North Dakota: Generally fair,\nsomewhat colder extreme east to\nnight Sunday Increasing cloudiness\nand not so cold possibly snow west\nportion.\nFor South Dakota: Generally fair\ntonight and Sunday somewhat colder\nextreme east tonight not so cold\nSunday.\nFor Montana: Cloudy, rain or snow\nSunday and west portion tonight ris\ning temperature tonight and east por\ntion Sunday.\nFor Minnesota: Generally fair\nsouth, mostly cloudy In north portion\nwith moderate cold wave northeast\ngenerally fair 8unday, not so cold\nwith moderate cold wave northeast\ngenerally fair Sunday, not so cold west\nportion.\nWBATHBR CONDITIONS\nA high pressure area extends from\nAlberta and Saskatchewan southward\nto Colorado and thence westward to\nOregon, Calgary, Alberta 30.3S Inches,\nwhile a low pressure area extends\nfrom Manitoba southward over the\nMississippi Valley. Another \"Low\"\nhas appeared over the north Pacific\ncoast, Seattle 28.94 Inches. Precipi\ntation has occurred at many places\nfrom the southern Plains States north\neastward to Manitoba and westward\nover the northern states to the north\nPacific coast. Temperatures dropped\nconsiderably over the northern Great\nPlains and over the northern Rocky\nMountain region, but readings are\nhigher over the Far Northwest.\nBismarck station barometer. Inches:\nH.tO. Reduced to sea level, 10.07.\nNunrUe, Si03 a, m.\nSansst, 41B8 p. m.\nWeather outlook for the period Nov,\nIt to Dec. 4:\nFor the region of the Great Lakes:\nGenerally fair Monday, rain or snow\nTuesday or Wednesday, followed by\ngenerally fair temperature below\nnormal Monday, rising to above nor\nmal middle of week and below normal\nduring latter part.\nFor the upper Mississippi and lower\nMissouri Valleys: Rain or snow north\nportion Monday or Tuesday and south\nTuesday or Wednesday, followed by\ngenerally fair with precipitation again\nby Friday or Saturday temperature\nbelow normal Monday, rising to\nabove normal Tuesday and Wednes\nday, falling below normal latter part\nof week.\nFor the northern and central Great\nPlains: Some snow or rain Indicated\nnorth portion first of week, otherwlst\nlittle precipitation Indloated: temper\nature rising to above normal Monday\nand Tuesday, falling below normal by\nThursday.\nPRECIPITATION\nFor Bismarck Station:\nTotal this month to date 41\nNormal thU month to date .49\nTotal, January 1st to date 1(01\nNormal, January 1st to date 15.69\nAccumulated excess to date 40\nNORTH DAKOTA POINTS\nLow- High\nest est Pet.\nBISMARCK, clear 40 Mi\nDevils Lake, clear 2 34 .04\nMlnot, clear 2 .00\nWllltston, pcldy 4 SI .90\nWBATHBR AT OTHER POINTS\nLow- High\nest est Pet.\nAberdeen. S. D.. clear 4 44 .M\nBoise, Idaho, cldy 34 41 .00\nCalgary, Alta., clear -I I .00\nChicago, 111., clear 44 .00\nDenver, Colo., clear ..14 SO .10\nDes Moines, Iowa, rain 34\nSI\nIt 44\n31\nDa\u00ad\nkota has the most representative dis\nplay of standard varieties of small\ngrain, seeds and corn the state has\never displayed at an international\ngrain and hay show, according to B.\nE. Groom, Greater North Dakota as\nsociation representative who is In\ncharge of the North Dakota exhibits\nhere.\nExhibitors include\u2014\nRye: Bemt Olson, White Earth\nN. S. Frauger, Mandan.\nGreat Northern beans: N. 8. Frau\nger, Mandan.\nCorn: Howard Goehring, Mandan\nN. S. Frauger, Mandan Ed Foes,\nHazen.\nEntries in the 4-H division were\u2014\nCorn: Lucas Fess, Hazen Freddie\nFoss, Hazen.\nLondon, Nov. 27. W) The\ngreatest fog In many years cur\ntained half of England Saturday,\nchoking transportation and en\ndangering pedestrians and motor\nists for a third day.\nWeather officials said the\n\"blackout\" was one of the worst\non record and predicted it would\ncontinue over the week-end. At\nleast 10 deaths had been at\ntributed to the murk.\nTrains and buses ran behind\nschedule or quit running alto\ngether. Shipping on the lower\nThames was halted. Pedestrians\nformed hand-to-hand chains to\nguide themselves along London's\nBoy Kills Father in\nArgument Over Girl\nLawrenceville, IU., Nov. 27.\u2014(JPi\u2014\nMarlon Hensley, 14, charged with kill\ning his father during an argument,\nover a neighbor girl's singing ability,\nwas held without bail Saturday in\nthe county jail on recommendation of\na coroner's jury.\nIs Sixth Arrest for\nMan Who Struck Girl\nMinneapolis, Nov. 27.\u2014VP)\u2014Eddl\nMay, 41, whose police .record Includes\nfive arrests for drunkenness and In\nvestigation, surrendered to Minneap\nolis police Saturday and admitted ae\nwas the auto driver who Wednesday\nSOLUTION TO PREVIOUS\nCONTRACT PROBLEM\nMrs. Robert B. Fuller of New York,\nvice president ef the Women's Aux\niliary of the American Contract Bridge\nLeague, has a distinguished tourna\nment record.\nShe now holds two national titles,\nthe women's pair and the women's\nteam of four, and also has the dis\ntinction of being the only woman ever\nto finish second in the National Mas\nters' Pair, which she did this year at\nAsbury, playing with Dr. Henry J.\nVogel.\n.04\nDodge City. Kans., cldy. 0 .10\nEdmonton, Alta., clear -16 0 .94\nGlendive. Mont., cldy. ..I 10 .00\nHavre, Mont., snowing I 10 .00\nHelena, Mont., cldy. it II .09\nHuron, S. D., clear\n4KQ42\nVKIi\nKQ7\nAQ7\n.04\nKamloops, B. C.. snow 10 34 .14\nKansas City, Mo., rain II 10 .99\nLewistown, Mont., cldy. 19 14 .00\nLos Angeles, Cal., clear 54 71 .00\nMiles City, Mont., snow 11 14 .92\nMpls.-St. Paul, M., snow 14 51 .99\nMobrldge, S. D\u201e clear.. 8 31 .90\nMoorhead, Minn., clear I 40 .02\nNo. Platte, Nebr., clear 24 50 .00\nOkla. City, Okla., rain\n\u00abJ73\nVJ10763\n1086\n\u2022a\nII\n40 .09\nPhoenix. Aria, clear 42 72 .00\nPierre, 8. D., clear 14 31 .02\nPrince Albert, 8., clear -2 14 .90\nQu'Appelle. 8., clear.... -4\n31\nRapid City, S. D.. clear 20\n50 .44\nEoseburg, Ore., cldy. 41 51 .00\nSt. Louis, Mo., foggy 42\nft\n.90\nSalt Lake City, U., pcldy. 21 44 .01\nSanta Fe. N. Hex clear 24 50 .00\nS. Marie, Mich. cldy. 14 42 .00\nSeattle. Wash., cldy. 44\n51 .04\nSheridan, Wyo., cldy. 24 II .90\n81oux City, Iowa, cldy. 24\n54\n.04\nSpokane, Wash., snow 34 42 .11\nSwift Current, S.. clear -4 12 .04\nThe Pas, Man., snowing -2 4 1.40\nWinnipeg, Man., cldy. 4 12 .24\nThere is no way of knowing how\nmany lives have been saved by the\nscavenging of the vulture tribe. Di\nsease and pestilence would have taken\na far greater toll of the human In\nhabitants of the globe were It no for\nthese repulsive creatures.\n*10888-\nKJ106\n\"AS\nVAQ04\nAJ942\n.15\nDuplicate\u2014N. and S. vul.\nWest Nerth East\n1* Pass 1* 2*\n2V Pass 7N.T. Pass\nPass Pass\nOpening lead\u2014V 2. 87\nBy Mrs. Robert Taller\nI've always liked to talk about the\nbridge hands which resulted favorblj\nfor me. Today I am choosing a hand\nwhich gave to my teammates and my\nself part of our margin in the wom\nen's team of four at Chicago. I sat\nNorth and when East opened the\nheart deuce, the hand looked safe,\nwon the first trick with the king and\nreturned a heart, but East discarded,\nExecutives of Corwin-Churchill Motors, Inc., Active in Civic Affairs\nN. O. Chore hill, general manager. Besides being closely associated\nwith sports in Bismarck, Churchill is a member of the local Rotary\nclub, B.P.OJC., Association of Commerce, Maternal Order of Eagles\nand Masonic bodies. He is well-known among sports enthusiasts of\nthe Northwest, having managed Bismarck's finest baseball teams, In\ncluding that which won the national semi-professional championship\nat Wichita, and also the Bismarck Phantoms, who won several state\nIndependent basketball titles. Mr. and Mrs. Churchill reside at lit\nMandan St. There are four children In the Churchill home.\nCart J. Reff, service manager. Rett has been associated with Cor\nwin-ChurchlU Motors, Inc., for 17 years. He is a member of the\nAmerican Legion, Association of Commerce and Knights of Columbus.\nMr. and Mrs. Reff reside at 619 Avenue F.\nR. E. Middaugh, office manager. A leading member of the Bis\nmarck Junior Association of Commerce, Middaugh also is a member\nof the Fraternal Order of Eagles. He has been with the Corwin\nChurchlll organisation for 11 years. Mr. and Mrs. Middaugh and their\ntwo children reside at 417 West Broadway.\nCharles J. Whittey, Jr., merchandise manager. Having been with\nthe Corwln-Churchtll organisation for a decade, Whittey is second\nvice president of the Bismarck Junior Association of Commerce and\na member of the B.P.O. Elks and Fraternal Order of Eagles. Mr. and\nMrs. Whittey live at 018 Third St.\nFled W. Clements, parts manager. Though he has been associated\nwith Corwin-Churchlll Motors, Inc., only since 1935, Clements has\nbeen with the Chrysler organisation for IS years. Mr. and Mrs. Clem\nents and their four children reside at 408 Second St., soon will move to\ntheir new home at 706 Sixth St.\nLondon Shrouded in\nOne of Greatest Fogs\nsidewalks behind leaders carrying\ntorches of biasing newspapers.\nThree persons fell into reser\nvoirs and a river while groping In\nthe darkness.\nThe three men in the crew of a\nGerman plane were killed Itlday\nnight when the craft crashed In\ntaking off from fog-chocked Croy\ndon airdrome. The plane struck a\nhangar and its exploding fuel\ntanks set fire to the building.\nFour motorists were killed early\nFriday in a crash in a London\nsuburb and several persons were\ninjured at the Nottingham railway\nstation when they tumbled off the\nplatform.\nnight struck down a 16-year-old girl\nMay was held in the city Jail on\ncharges of driving while drunk and\n\u2022failure to give aid to a person injured\nin an accident.\nTrouble-Maker Is\nHanged in Palestine\nHaifa, Palestine, Nov. 27.\u2014*\u2022\u2014\nSheik Oarhan Saadi, bearded trouble\nmaker of the Holy Land, was hanged\nSaturday in the ancient fortren of\nthe medieval Cruasaders at Acre\u2014the\nfirst to face punishment under the\nnew military courts martial to curb\nterrorism.\nThe sand smelt has a telescopic\nmouth when the fish approaches Its\nprey, the mouth shoots out and\nsr apt it up.\nMdSemigKBy \u00bbm Briidl&c\nPLANS PLAY TO MAKE SLAM\nMrs. Robert Fuller, Champion Player, Scores Seven No Trump\nContract Against Odds\nBy WILLIAM E. McKENNEY\n(Secretary, American Ceo tract Bridge Leagae)\nThis is the eleventh In a series\nof 13 articles Illustrating the play\nof national champions In tourna\nments where they won renown.\nhaving opened a singleton. This now\ngave me only 12 of the needed 18\ntricks as the club king seemed marked\nwith East.\nI next played the ace of clubs, es\ntablishing the king for East. Then I\ncashed the ace of hearts and five di*\nmonds, and on the last diamond Bast\nhad to choose between parting with a\ntpade or the high club.\nDummy's cards were the ace and\nfive of spades, the nine of hearts and\nthe nine of clubs. West now held the\nJack-seven-three of spades and the\njack-ten of hearts. I held the queen\nof clubs and four spades.\nI discarded the queen of clubs snd\nEast gave up the king of clubs. I\nthen won the next trick in the dum\nmy with the nine of clubs snd took\nthe remaining tricks with the ace,\nking and queen of spades, thus mak\ning my contract.\nContract Problem\n(Selutlea la next Issae)\nSouth's contract is three no\ntrump. East and West have\nwon the first two tricks in\nspades and South has won the\nthird. South now plays the\ndiamond ace and West plays\nthe nine. South leads the eight\nof diamonds and West plays\nthe three. East wins with the\nqueen. What should he re\nturn?\n88\nVKQ4\nKJ1082\nJ4J\nTHE BISMARCK TRIBUNE. SATURDAY, NOVEMBER 27.1987\ndkQTf\nV878\nQS4\n*8878\n(Blind)\n(Blind\nDuplicate\u2014E. snd W. vul\nOpener\u20144 5. 87\n(Copyright, 1987, NEA Service,\nlac.)\nComing across the monarchs of\nthe woods lying exhausted with\ntheir antlers hopelessly locked\nafter hours of struggling, Knut\nson severed the antlers of one of\nthe bucks to free him. After a\nfew minutes, the bucks weakly\nregained their shaky legs and\nOraaS Pacific Hotel\nMrs. E. G. Sailer, Stanton Florence\nJtss, Harmon Mr*. Ralph Itakln,\nHazen Lillian Skallet, Huff Mr*.\nWilliam Bauer, Linton E. Sberhard,\nNew Salem Mr. and Mra. R. T. Coutts,\nBeach and N. Villain and B. Johnson,\nBillings, Mont.\nDeaths\nHomer Dobbs, 17, Barley, Minn., at\n3:41 a. m. Saturday, in a local hoepl-\nPhilip Ackerman, 46, 1M Are.\nWest, Thursday.\nDr. J. O. Amson returned Saturday\nfrom an extended visit in California\nand points along the North Pacific\ncoast.\nGeorge Bittis, Bismarck merchant,\nwill be brought before Justice of the\nPeace Spencer Sell Monday to answer\ncharges of selling unstamped dgar\nets, Sell said Saturday.\nFuneral services for Dr. L. S. Hoff\nman, MOtt dentist fatally Injured la\nan automobile accident last Sunday\nnight, who died in a local hospital\nThursday, will be held In the Convert\nFuneral home Sunday at 2 p. m.\nBurial will be at New Salem.\nOscar E. Erlckson, Insurance com\nmissioner. left Saturday for New York\nto attend a national four-day meet\ning of state Insurance commissioners.\nThey will determine a uniform policy\nin evaluating Insurance companies,\nreal estate and bond holdings.\nLast rites for Mrs. Mary Margaret\nPurvis, 83, sister of A. D. McKlnnon,\nwho died here suddenly Wednesday\nwere conducted in St. Mary's pro\ncathedral here Saturday morning with\nRev. Robert Feehan officiating. Pall\nbearers were B. O. Ward, John Hoff\nman. A. Y. Haglund, C. S. Possum, J.\nN. Roherty, and J. B. Smith.\nBen. C. Larkin, president of the\nstate railroad commission, left Satur\nday for Washington to attend a hear\ning before the Interstate Commerce\ncommission In the general 18 per cent\nfreight rate Increases asked by the\nrailroads. Also opposing the request\ntill be J. C. Winter, the commission's\nirsffic expert.\n(J ONTINJJE\nState, WPA to Join\nIn Getting Water\nOn M'Kenzie Land\nItoe project near Wllllston is the first\nto be given such Joint approval.\nTe Cost 8808,888\nThe tract to be Irrigated consists of\n8,000 acres lying In the Missouri river\nbottoms on the McKensle county side\nof the bridge at Wllllston. Tentative\nfigures place the cost of the develop\nment at about 8300.000 of which ap\nproximately 8100,000 would be sup\nplied by the Rural Rehabilitation cor\nporation and the remainder would Be\na contribution by the federal govern\nment.\nUnder the plan outlined, families\nwould be allooated 80 acres of Irri\ngated land and placed on the tract to\nmake their homes. Members of the\nwater commission said Saturday that\nthe co-operation of the Farm Secur\nlty administration would be sought\nIn connection with the settlement\nproblem.\nThe Idea Is to take families who\nT/lsh to go on Irrigated land and settle\nthem under such conditions that they\ncould reasonably be expected to make\na suooess of their operations. At the\nsame time the uplands vacated by\nthem could be transferred to otha/s\nso as to enlarge upland holdings and\nmake them into more economic units.\nApproval of the Lewis and Clark\npioject, yarned after the nearby\nbridge, clears the way for similar de\nvelopments elsewhere In the state.\nAmong these are projects In the\nPainted Woods bottoms In southern\nMcLsen and northern Burleigh ooun\n'ies and the Stout project In southern\nBurleigh and northern Emmons.\nDiamonds\nWeMhv Rings.\nF. A. Knowles\nmM OiaawaS Slate tar Si\nIff1\nCLEMENTS\nAntler-Entwined Deer\nAre Saved From Death\nTowner, N. D., Nor. 27.\u2014Locked\nin a battle to the death 10 miles\nnorth of here on Game Warden\nChris Steigen's farm, two buck\ndeer owe their lives to the humane\nImpulse and the saw of Lloyd\nKnutson.\nmoved off in different directions.\nBtelgen previously had discov\nered the plight of the\nand figured the humane thing to\ndo would be to shoot both. How\never, he decided to call Edward\nAnderson, deputy game warden of\nTowner, in consultation. Dep\nuty Sheriff Joe Strang also was\nashed to aid in the deliberations.\nWhen the trio arrived at the\nsoene of the battle they ware as\ntounded to find the bucks gone\nbut soon learned what had tran\nspired and declared Knutson hsd\nhad the best idea after all.\nGayda Sings Words\nto II DuceY Tunes\nTl/TOST wfdely\nquoted man\nin Italy, even\nmore than Pre\nmier Mussolini,\nis Virginio Gay\nda, confidant of\nII'Duce and\neditor of Tl Gi\nornale d'ltalia.\nA\nNewspapermen\nknow his edi\ntorials reflect\nthe official\nFascist view\npoint\nOayda\nFuneral Rites Set for\nPhilip Ackerman, 66\nFuneral services for Philip Acker\nman, 88, long-time North Dakota resi\ndent who died at his home at 108 Av\nenue O Thursday morning, will be\nconducted from the Webb Funeral\nParlors at 2 p. m. Sunday. Mr. Acker\nman came to Bismarck in October\nfrom near Anamooee, where he had\nlived since 1802.\nBorn In Russia, Ackerman married\nMiss Elisabeth Belts in Rumania, Dee.\n8,1801, and came to the United States\nin 1809, settling Immediately on a\nhomestead near Anamooee.\nIn addition to his widow, he leaves\nseven children, three brothers, three\nslsteie and six grandchildren. Da ugh\nten are Maggie, Katie, Hilda and\nAnnie. The two sons are Gust and\nAndrew.\nRev. Benjamin Schlipf, pastor of\nthe Oerman Baptist church here, will\nofficiate at the servloes and burial\nwill be in Falrvew cemetery here.\nAssistant Secretary\nOf Interior Is Dead\nWashington, Nor. 27\u2014 (*)\u2014'Theodore\nWalters, 81, first assistant secretary of\nthe Interior, died Saturday at the\nnaval hospital. Walters, a resident of\nCUdwell, Idaho, went to the hospital\nseveral days ago to undergo an opera\ntion for gallstone. Early Vtiday, ho\ncontracted pneumonia.\nCapitol Elevators\nCover 17,000 Miles\nBelieve it or not, says Ed Nel\nson, state superintendent of\nbuildings, but three capttol eleva\ntors hare trareled nearly 17,000\nmiles over a greased track only\n241 feet high.\nCage No. 1, the first Installed\nin the statehouie four years ago,\nholds the reoord with S.SM miles.\nThe second cage traveled over\n8,000 miles and the third 4,500\nSTATE\nSat. SOB.\n\"CEILING\nZERO\"\nwith\nJAMES\nCAGNEY\nPAT\nO'BRIEN\nSTUART ERWIN\nJUNE TRAVIS\nShews at 1 and 8\nPrices lOe and tie\nHOMER DODDS, 37,\nAutopsy Ordered to Determine\nCause of Death of Son of\nPioneer Family\nAn autopsy to determine the cause\nof death of Homer Dodds, 87, son of\na pioneer Dawson, N. D., farm family,\nin a local hospital at 3:45 a. jn., Satur\nday, was to be conducted Saturday\nafternoon, physicians here said.\nDodds was brought to Steele, N. D.\nTuesday night from Bagley, Minn,\nwhere he had lived for the past three\nyears, and was brought to the hos\npltal here Thursday night. According\nto a brother, Richard Dodds of Steele,\nhe was unconscious when brought to\nSteele by automobile and did not re\ngain consciousness afterwards. He was\ntaken sick suddenly Nov. 19. Decision\nto conduct a post mortem examina\ntion was made when doctors here\nwere unable to say immediately what\ncaused his death.\nBorn Sept. 14, 1800, the son of Mr.\nand Mrs. Robert N. Dodds, who home\nsteaded near Dawson in the early '80s,\nDodds had lived at Steele until he\nwent to Bagley to work three years\nago. He was married about 15 years\nago to Grace Markham at Dawson.\nHe leaves, in addition to his brother\nRichard, his mother, Mrs. Clara\nDodds, who lives with a daughter at\nSteele, two sisters and two other\nbrothers. The sisters are Mrs. Leo\nMayer, Steele, and Mrs. W. W. Hicks,\nMiles City, Mont. Brothers other than\nRichard are Robert of Dawson and\nArthur of Dallas, Texas.\nAineral services will be from the\nDawson Methodist church at 2 p. m.,\nMonday and burial will be in the\nDawson oemetery.\nParole of Bad Check\nPasser Is Suspended\nBecause he allegedly continued to\nwrite worthless checks after being\nwarned against it, when a 30-day Jail\nsentence on a similar charge was sus\npended a month ago, Francis T. Klein,\nMandan, faces a prospect of spending\nthe next 30 days in the Burleigh coun\nty Jail.\nKlein surrendered here IMday\nmorning on a bad check charge and\nwas brought before Police Magistrate\nE. 8. Allen, who revoked the suspension\nand ordered Klein to serve the time\nU. Jail.\nSeven checks, all of them worthless,\nsnd said to have been written by\nKlein, were in Allen's possession Sat\nurday. The total amount of the checks\ndid not exceed 825, Allen said, and\nncne pf them was for more than 85.\nRoosevelt to Leave\nFor Cruise Tonight\nWashington, Nov. 27.\u2014{/Pi\u2014Presl\ndent Roosevelt will leave late Satur\nday night for his postponed fishing\ncruise off the Florida coast. The\nnine-day rail and water Journey will\nadd more than 2,500 miles to his re\ncently-achieved presidential travel\nrecord of 114,008 miles.\nMr. Roosevelt will go directly to\nMiami by special train and embark\non the yacht Potomac Monday morn\ning.\nAfter four or five days' fishing, he\nwill reboard his train for Warm\nSprings, Ga., to enjoy a belated\nThanksgiving dinner with the Infan\ntile paralysis patients.\nMorals Squad Too\nFast Girl Freed\nMinneapolis, Nov. 27.\u2014VP)\u2014The\nquestion of who had the dime\nwhen the police morals squad\nraided the Paradise Bar and Night\nClub was the paramount issue\nSaturday in municipal court.\nA member of the morals squad\ntestified he had shaken dloe with\nBeatrice Frakle, who was behind\nthe bar's dice counter.\nA1 Palmers ten, head of the\nmorals squad, testified he entered\nthe place as the game was fin\nished, and arrested the girl on a\ngambling charge.\nThe defense contended that\nwhen the arrest was made the\ndime to pay for the game bad not\nchanged hands.\n\"If that is the case,\" said Judge\nJoseph Polrier, \"there wss no\nmonetary consideration Involved.\nCase dismissed.\"\nYou'd never forgive us if\nwe didn't tell you\nITS THEIR PER\nFECT PICTURE TO-\nGETHER!\nTyrone Power\nand\nLoretta Young\nin\n\"Second\nHoneymoon\"\nIt's Tyrone and Loretta! Their\nlave Is news again, in a new\nand deeper way for thla\ntlma they mean it with all\ntheir hearts!\nAlso Our Gang Comedy\nand\nMickey Mouse Cartoon\nShowing Tonight\nand Sunday\nS u n a y a 2 -4 -7 -9\nPlease note: After the\nlast performance Sunday\nthe theatre will be closed\nfor reseating until De\ncember 5th\nIDISMARCIC\n0 THEATRE\nGood Guesser\nIdfle J. Cleveland, 222 Fifteenth\nSt., hopes he will repeat his\nprise-winning guessing of a week\nago in the football contests this\nweek. Cleveland's guesses last\nweek wan him second prise In The\nBismarck Tribune's contest.\nPROMINENT MAYVILLE\nBUSINESS MAN DIES\nHeart Attack It Fatal to E. A.\nBjelde, 75 Cams to City\nin 1885\nMayville, N. D, Nov. 27.\u2014m\u2014E. A.\nBjelde, 75, prominent business man\nhere for more than 50 years, died of\na heart attack at his home here early\nSaturday.\nHe Ipd not been 111 and Friday was\nattending to his business as usual.\nEarly Saturday he suffered a pain in\none shoulder and died in a few min\nutes.\nFuneral arrangements await word\nfrom a daughter in Montana.\nMr. Bjelde was born in Norway and\nwhen 8 years old came with his par\nents to the United States. He came\nto Mayville In 1885 and worked as a\ntinner's apprentice for three yean\nand then became a partner of 8. J.\nJohnson in the hardware business\nwhich he operated with a son, Du\npant, at the time of his death.\nSurvivors are his widow, whom he\nmarried at Morris, Minn., and three\nchildren.\nGET WEDDING LICENSE\nSan Diego, Calif., Nov. 27.\u2014(\u00a3\"\u2014A\nmarriage license was Issued Friday to\nPloyd T. Peterson, 24, San Francisco,\nind Katherine Larsen, as, Kermlt,\nN. D.\nCAPITOL\nENDS TODAY\nwia\"\nHIIFIITillE\nIEIIULI I\n1\nIMRIEL\nIII RtllE\nfna Si Say ly is\nr.awoDiMowf-\nSUN.- MON.- TUES.\nHere's\nSomething\nNew\nYou've never seen a picture\nquite like \"Garrick\"! It's\ngay, it's funny, it's young,\nit's romantic... it's simply\nswell!\nft","height":"27080","width":"20640"}}
